{% call getstarted.section("Working in XD") -%}

  <h4>Using the patterns</h4>

  <p>Find your desired FTS pattern in the Libraries panel and drop it into your design. To replace a pattern, highlight the parent pattern in the Layers panel and drop a different pattern on top of it. To reset an edited pattern back to default, right-click on the pattern in the Layers panel and select <em>Reset to Main State</em>. <strong>These actions will erase or reset any changes made.</strong></p>

  {% call getstarted.example(palette='lightest') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/getstarted/fts-starter-kit/fts-starter-kit-using-patterns.svg' | url }}" alt="FTS starter kit - Using the patterns" style="--example-img-max-width: 872px;">
  {%- endcall %}

  <h4>Component states</h4>

  <p>Each FTS pattern in XD has various <strong>Component States</strong> or toggles that show design specs like layout, spacing, etc. Toggling each component state is a good way to learn what elements in a pattern can and cannot be changed. Component states are a starting point where you can familiarize yourself with FTS patterns, you can customize them further in Drupal.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Default State</strong> - The default appearance of each pattern when first dropped into your design.</li>
    <li><strong>Blueprint</strong> - Displays element labels in patterns which also correspond to the fields in Drupal.</li>
    <li><strong>Layout options</strong> - Displays some examples of layout configurations, additional options are available in Drupal.</li>
    <li><strong>Alignment</strong> - Displays alignment options for select elements, like calls to action or text.</li>
    <li><strong>Spacing</strong> - Displays the correct spacing in between each element according to the design system.</li>
    <li><strong>Themes</strong> - Displays various sets of themed elements according to the design system.</li>
    <li><strong>Pattern builder demo link</strong> - Displays a link to further customize each pattern using the pattern builder website.</li>
  </ul>

  {% call getstarted.example(palette='lightest') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/getstarted/fts-starter-kit/fts-starter-kit-component-states.svg' | url }}" alt="FTS starter kit - Component states" style="--example-img-max-width: 872px;">
  {%- endcall %}

  <h4>Element labeling</h4>

  <p>In the Blueprint component state, elements are labeled according to how the fields are labeled on the pattern builder website or in Drupal. If you want to add, change, or remove something, look for the corresponding fields that match each label. There are a lot of fields for even simple FTS patterns, but following the blueprint makes it easy to find the correct fields.</p>

  {% call getstarted.example(palette='lightest') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/getstarted/fts-starter-kit/fts-starter-kit-element-labeling.svg' | url }}" alt="FTS starter kit - Element labeling" style="--example-img-max-width: 872px;">
  {%- endcall %}

{%- endcall %}

{% call getstarted.section("Working in Drupal") -%}

  <h4>Pattern options</h4>

  <p>The patterns available in the FTS starter kit are the same as the ones on the pattern builder website or in Drupal which makes it easy to recreate your design when building a page. More patterns will be added to the FTS starter kit in the near future.</p>

  {% call getstarted.example(palette='lightest') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/getstarted/fts-starter-kit/fts-starter-kit-pattern-options.svg' | url }}" alt="FTS starter kit - Pattern options" style="--example-img-max-width: 698px;">
  {%- endcall %}

  <h4>Adding patterns</h4>

  <p>With a few clicks, an FTS pattern can be added in Drupal. When the new pattern loads, you can reference the element labels in the Blueprint component state to know exactly which fields are being used to create the design of the pattern.</p>

  {% call getstarted.example(palette='lightest') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/getstarted/fts-starter-kit/fts-starter-kit-adding-patterns.svg' | url }}" alt="FTS starter kit - Adding patterns" style="--example-img-max-width: 872px;">
  {%- endcall %}

  <h4>Customizing patterns</h4>

  <p>Once an FTS pattern is loaded in Drupal, it can be customized with just a few clicks. Element labels make it easy to find the fields in Drupal that you can use to customize an FTS pattern. To make a change, select the dropdown to see what options are available. When you change an element like a background color, other elements will also change to fit the new theme. To add or remove a component like a call to action, there are buttons for those actions. This continuous loop of working with FTS patterns in XD and moving to Drupal takes practice, but it can reduce working time by a lot once you learn the process.</p>

  {% call getstarted.example(palette='lightest') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/getstarted/fts-starter-kit/fts-starter-kit-customizing-patterns.svg' | url }}" alt="FTS starter kit - Customizing patterns" style="--example-img-max-width: 872px;">
  {%- endcall %}

{%- endcall %}

{% call getstarted.section("Best practices") -%}

  <p>Our goal with the FTS starter kit and Drupal is to give users the tools they need to design and develop pages by themselves. There are endless ways to customize FTS patterns or design pages in XD and Drupal. However, there are also endless ways to create something that does not align to our brand standards or design system. When customizing FTS patterns or building pages in XD or Drupal, here are resources that will help your work stay on brand and aligned to our design system.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Design system <a href="../../foundations/">Foundations</a> or common FTS layouts like <a href="../../components/card">Cards</a></li>
    <li><a href="https://www.redhat.com/en/about/brand/standards" target="_blank">Brand standards</a> like icons, illustrations, photography, etc.</li>
    <li>FTS <a href="https://www.redhat.com/en/demo-fts-patterns" target="_blank">patterns</a> or <a href="https://www.redhat.com/en/demo-fts-layouts" target="_blank">layout</a> demo pages</li>
  </ul>

